In reality, floating islands refer to naturally occurring accumulations of plant matter and vegetation that can float on the surface of a body of water. They typically form in lakes or marshes and consist of a mat made out of soil, roots, and other organic materials. However, the concept of an island floating in the open ocean or any additional geographic feature not attached to a land mass and suspended in the air is mostly fictional and due to human imagination or science fiction literature.

Some proposed artificial islands are made of lightweight materials that can float over the surface of the water and can be employed for habitation, agriculture, and energy generation. These islands are still anchored to a body of water for stability and do not float freely in the sky or open ocean the same way natural floating islands do.

In scientific and conservation perspectives, floating islands have benefits, providing habitat and protection for wildlife.
